La Junta de Educación del Distrito Escolar Unificado Corona-Norco está actualmente en el proceso de llenar la vacante del Superintendente debido al Anuncio de Retiro del Superintendente Dr. Lin y le gustaría su opinión. La Junta ha contratado a Leadership Associates, una firma de búsqueda de terceros para ayudar en el proceso de contratación. Como parte de ese proceso, Leadership Associates recopilará y compilará los resultados de la encuesta de la comunidad para la consideración de la Junta. Todas las sumisiones de encuestas y las aportaciones del público recibidas serán anónimos.

Gracias de antemano por sus comentarios sobre este importante proceso de toma de decisiones. Por favor complete la encuesta aquí: https://es.surveymonkey.com/r/5JPC35V.

Update: We are aware our Superintendent Search Survey e-mail has broken links. We are working with our broadcast messaging provider to address the issue. Thank you for your patience.

The Corona-Norco Unified School District Board of Education is currently in the process of filling the Superintendent vacancy due to Superintendent Dr. Lin’s Retirement Announcement and would like your input. The Board has hired Leadership Associates, a third-party search firm to assist in the hiring process. As part of that process, Leadership Associates will collect and compile community survey results for the Board’s consideration. All survey submissions and public input received will be anonymous.

post_text:
¿Su estudiante tiene problemas para iniciar sesión en su dispositivo emitido por el Distrito? 💻

K-12:
El nombre de usuario es su número estudiantil (número de 6 dígitos).

K-4:
Primer inicial de nombre en MAYÚSCULA + primer inicial de apellido nombre minúscula + Fecha de nacimiento sin ceros antes el mes y el día.

Ejemplo: John Smith, FDN – 7/9/1995, la contraseña = Js791995

5-12:
Si están mayor del 4o grado, entonces tendrán que crear su propia contraseña. Si es la primera vez que inicia sesión, deben usar la contraseña predeterminada anterior y se les pedirá que establezcan una nueva contraseña para sí mismos en su primer inicio de sesión.

post_text:
Is your student having trouble signing in to their district-issued device? 💻

K-12:
Your username is your student ID number.

K-4:
CAPITAL First initial of first name + lowercase first initial of last name + Date of Birth with no leading zeros before the month and day

Example: John Smith, DOB – 7/9/1995, password = Js791995

5-12:
If they are above 4th grade, then they will need to create their own password. If it is their first time logging in, they should use the default password above, and they will be prompted to set a new password for themselves on their first login.

post_text:
Beginning Tuesday, August 11th, Curbside Grab & Go meals will take place at most CNUSD school sites, on the first day of each week. Students will receive breakfast and lunch for each school day.

Please note: Meals are no longer free for all students, and students will be charged the free or paid price depending on their eligibility for the school meal program. Students do not need to be present, but parents and/or students are required to provide valid CNUSD pin numbers for all meals, just as we do during the typical school year. A student may receive only one bag of food per week.

For more information, please visit https://www.cnusd.k12.ca.us/meals.

A partir del martes 11 de agosto, las comidas Grab & Go se llevarán a cabo en la mayoría de las escuelas del CNUSD, el primer día de cada semana. Los estudiantes recibirán desayuno y almuerzo por cada día escolar.

Tenga en cuenta: Las comidas ya no son gratuitas para todos los estudiantes, y se les cobrará el precio gratis o pagado según su elegibilidad para el programa de comidas escolares. Los estudiantes no necesitan estar presentes, pero se requiere que los padres y/o estudiantes proporcionen números de PIN válidos del CNUSD para todas las comidas, tal como lo hacemos durante el año escolar típico. Un estudiante puede recibir solo una bolsa de comida por semana.

Para obtener más información, visite https://www.cnusd.k12.ca.us/meals.

De parte de nuestra Junta de Educación, Superintendente y Gabinete Ejecutivo, nos gustaría reconocer el desarrollo de los acontecimientos recientes en nuestro país debido a la muerte del Sr. George Floyd. Este incidente ha arrojado una luz sobre el racismo que sigue existiendo en nuestro país. Realizamos los incidentes que han ocurrido en los últimos días, en toda nuestra nación, han tenido un profundo impacto en nuestra comunidad y en nuestros estudiantes. Avanzando, nos comprometemos a comprender el impacto del racismo y cómo podemos seguir dando pasos hacia una sociedad socialmente justa.

Por favor, vea nuestro compromiso adjunto a nuestra comunidad.

A continuación se presentan enlaces para apoyar a estudiantes, personal y familias:
- Recursos de Salud Mental del CNUSD https://bit.ly/2U8Pn0H
- CNUSD Sala Virtual de Calma https://bit.ly/2XsMutB
- Recursos de Terapia Gratuita a través de Care Solace https://bit.ly/2XwBcF0

On behalf of our Board of Education, Superintendent, and Executive Cabinet, we would like to recognize the unfolding of recent events in our country due to the death of Mr. George Floyd. This incident has shed a light on racism which continues to exist in our country. We realize the incidents which have occurred over the past several days, throughout our nation, have had a profound impact on our community and on our students. Moving forward, we commit ourselves in understanding the impact of racism and how we can continue to take steps towards a socially-just society.

Please see our attached commitment to our community.

Below are links to support for students, staff and families:
- CNUSD Mental Health Resources https://bit.ly/2U8Pn0H
- CNUSD Virtual Calming Room https://bit.ly/2XsMutB
- Free Therapy Resources via Care Solacehttps://bit.ly/2XwBcF0

Today we share with you a new story filmed prior to the school closures. Did you know that CNUSD serves students of all ages? At the CNUSD Adult School, we do just that! Here our students, some of whom are parents of our traditional students, attend classes that range from learning a second language like English or Spanish, to life-saving techniques like CPR. Our Adult Education program offers a wide-range of topics to further enrich our students' lives by learning new skills not just for themselves but for their families.

To learn more, visit: https://adulted.cnusd.k12.ca.us/

We're back to share another story filmed prior to the school closures. As part of Mental Health Awareness Week, we want to highlight Eleanor Roosevelt High School, Eastvale CA Unity Program. In Unity, our resilient students get a chance to openly express themselves by learning about each other and their shared struggles, expanding their world view and building a community of support.

To find mental health resources and activities visit: https://www.cnusd.k12.ca.us/mentalhealth.

post_text:
Here's a great way to honor your High School Seniors!

To add a frame to your profile picture:
1. Go to www.facebook.com/profilepicframes.
2. Select a frame from the search bar at the top. You can search the keyword "CNUSD".
3. CNUSD frames will have "Proud of my Senior 2020" along with the respective High School name in the title.
4. Select the frame you want to use.
5. Click Use as Profile Picture to save.
6. Share your new profile photo!

We want to take a moment to thank our wonderful community, staff, parents, and students especially at Riverview Elementary School - Norco, CA and Norco High School for working together yesterday during the #MannFire incident in Norco. With the swift actions of our Transportation and Support Services Departments, we were able to successfully evacuate our Riverview students safety and seamlessly to Norco High School where all students were picked up by their families.

The willingness of our community, staff, and parents to work together, allowed us to ensure the safety of all our students and staff members.

Thank you.

post_text:
#MannFire Update #2:

CNUSD Families,

As an update, the "Mann Fire" currently located in the Santa Ana River Bottom in Norco continues to burn. As stated in the previous message, Riverview Elementary School is the only school that is being evacuated to Norco High School as a precaution. With the exception of Riverview Elementary School, there are no additional schools in CNUSD affected. Due to air quality, all schools are placed on inclement weather schedule.

To assist residents in Norco and Jurupa that are being evacuated, the Red Cross has identified Corona High School and Jurupa Valley High School as evacuation centers.

Thank you for your cooperation, should you have any questions please direct them to your school site. We will continue to stay in contact with Cal Fire and the Riverside County Sheriff’s Departments, and keep you apprised of any new information affecting our schools.

#MannFire Update #1:

CNUSD Families,

So you are aware, there is currently a brush fire in the Santa Ana River Bottom on the Jurupa side. Riverview Elementary is in close proximity to the fire, and the evacuation orders of neighborhood houses will prompt the school to be evacuated as a precaution. Riverview Elementary students will be transported to Norco High School, parents should bring proper identification to retrieve students. We are in contact with Cal Fire and there are currently no additional schools affected. We do understand that this fire is affecting air quality in our region and we are recommending inclement weather for our school sites.

We will continue to be in close contact with Cal Fire and the Riverside County Sheriff's Department should any new information regarding our schools become available. We will continue to keep you updated. This message will also be shared on the District website at: www.cnusd.k12.ca.us

Career Technical Education (CTE) provides students of all ages with the academic and technical skills, knowledge, and training necessary to succeed in future careers and to become lifelong learners. CTE prepares student learners for the world of work by introducing them to workplace competencies, and makes academic content accessible to students by providing it in a hands-on context.

Meet our 2020 CTE Ambassadors who challenge all students (no matter their age) to ask themselves how they want to make a difference when they grow up!

post_text:
A message from Superintendent Dr. Lin on the recent tragedy that has struck our CNUSD community.

Today we find ourselves in profound sadness as we learned of the tragic loss of three young lives, two of which were CNUSD students, who were involved in a fatal car crash over the weekend in Temescal Valley. There is no greater tragedy than the death of a young person, and we offer our sincere condolences and continued support to the families. Counselors are on the Santiago and Centennial High School campuses today to provide support for students and staff and will be in place for as long as necessary, as this tragic news impacts our entire community. On behalf of the Board of Education and Cabinet, we wish to convey our wholehearted condolences to all those affected by this sudden loss.

Dr. Michael Lin
CNUSD Superintendent

post_text:
🖥️ The #HourOfCode is at its core not about learning a brand new skill in just one hour. One hour isn’t enough to learn how to code. It's about increasing access to computer science by breaking stereotypes and opening doors. Somebody may learn programming concepts like loops, conditionals, or basic debugging through the Hour of Code. But a much more important goal is for students and teachers to learn that computer science is fun — you can start at any age, in any classroom, even if you don’t have a computer.

➡️For fun, free ways to participate in an #HourOfCode visit: https://bit.ly/2LCQCRo

Computer Science Education Week

Riverside County Office of Education
December 9, 2019 at 11:29 AM ·

On Saturday RCOE hosted the first-ever Riverside County Esports League semifinals competition. More than 70 students on school teams from fifteen districts/charter schools across Riverside County competed for the chance to advance to the championship finals tournament to be held on January 11 at Norco College.

Thirteen teams from south Riverside County competed in the morning tournament and 12 teams from north Riverside County competed in the afternoon.

Congratulations to the top four teams from the north and south semifinal advancing to finals:

Chaparral High School, Temecula Valley USD
Murrieta Valley High School, Murrieta Valley USD
Orange Vista High School, Val Verde USD
Paloma Valley High School, Perris UHSD
Patriot High School, Jurupa USD
Centennial High School, Corona Norco USD
Arlington High School, Riverside USD
Eleanor Roosevelt High School, Corona Norco USD

➡️Report rumored threats to a trusted adult rather than spreading on social media.
➡️Watch: https://youtube.com/watch?v=q0HCQZ2V8VE
shared_text:
CORONACA.GOV
School Threats to Centennial High School

City of Corona Police Department
December 6, 2019 at 9:34 AM ·

In the evening hours on December 5, 2019, the Corona Police Department along with School Administration from Centennial High School were contacted regarding rumors of a school shooting to occur Friday, December 6, 2019. After a lengthy investigation, the Corona Police Department Investigators found no credible threat to students.

The Corona Police Department and the Corona Unified School District takes every rumor and threat to the safety of the students in the Corona Norco Unified School District seriously and will investigate them until all leads are exhausted. This investigation was a good reminder not to spread gossip or rumors without knowing the source. If you See Something, Say Something. Report these types of rumors or suspicious behavior immediately to the proper authorities to investigate, instead of spreading on social media.

If you have further information about the incident, please contact the Police Officer assigned to Centennial High School, Officer Clary at 951-739-5670 Ext: 20021.
https://uqfh5.app.goo.gl/fLhi

post_text: The Corona-Norco Adult School Training Center was dedicated to former Board President, Mr. Cipriano Hernandez. He was the first Latino elected as President of the Corona-Norco Unified School District Board of Trustees, from 1971 to 1973. He was also a member of the committee for Best Education formed in 1967 to develop and promote a plan for desegregation. Read more about Mr. Cipriano Hernandez: https://bit.ly/37iWwQY.

#SafeSchoolsWeek #CNUSDisKind #KindnessRivCo
shared_text:
Riverside County Office of Education is feeling excited.
October 21, 2019 at 7:00 AM ·

During America's Safe Schools Week, October 21-27, 2019, Riverside County Superintendent of Schools Dr. Judy D. White is encouraging students to become Campus Kindness Ambassadors. The goal of the campaign is to motivate students, staff, parents, and community residents to build relationships at school. When people know one another and care about their school, campus safety, discipline, and student attendance improve.

For Monday, October 21: Reach out to a classmate and make a new friend.

post_text:
Did you know that you can work towards and even graduate with an Associate's Degree while attending high school? At John F. Kennedy Middle College High School, students can enroll concurrently at Norco College and still enjoy life as a high school student. Check our why our students like being at such a unique campus!

JFK will be hosting a Parent information Night on October, 28, 2019 at 6:30 p.m.

post_text: As part of Bullying Prevention month, our CNUSD 4th Graders were encouraged to promote kindness and respect at the World Kindness Youth Conference earlier this week. Thank you to the Simple Acts of Care and Kindness (SACK) Foundation for all you do for our students! 😀
